[h1]Creating Linear Gradients [/h1]

CSS3 gradients enable you to display smooth transitions between two or more specified colors. CSS3 defines two types of gradients: [b]Linear[/b] and [b]Radial[/b]. 

To create a linear gradient, you must define at least two color stops. Color stops are the colors among which you want to render smooth transitions. You can also set a starting point and a direction - or an angle - along with the gradient effect.
In the example below, the colors blue and black are used to create a linear gradient from top to bottom.[code format="css" codeId="599"]div {
   float: left;
   width: 300px; 
   height: 100px;
   margin: 4px;
   color: #FFF;  
   [b]background:-moz-linear-gradient[/b](DeepSkyBlue, Black);
}[/code]
This syntax works in Mozilla (-moz). If you work with a different browser, add the corresponding prefix, so that the browser understands the gradient.

[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2687" width="100%"]
[note]You can use [b]color names[/b], [b]Hex values[/b], [b]RGB[/b], or [b]HSL [/b]colors to define the gradient color.[/note]

[h1]Direction of the Gradient[/h1]

The direction of the gradient can be changed.
In the example below, the first gradient starts at [b]left[/b], moving [b]right[/b]; the second one runs from [b]bottom [/b]to [b]top[/b].[code format="css" codeId="602"]div.first {
   float: left;
   width: 300px; 
   height: 100px;
   margin: 4px;
   color: #FFF;  
   background:-moz-linear-gradient([b]left[/b], blue, green, white);
} 
div.second { 
   float: left;
   width: 300px; 
   height: 100px;
   margin: 4px;
   background:-moz-linear-gradient([b]bottom[/b], blue, green, white);
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2690" width="100%"]
[note][b]left[/b], [b]right[/b], [b]top[/b], and [b]bottom [/b]are supported values for the gradient direction. You can also use their various combinations to specify direction (e.g., [b]bottom right[/b])[/note]

[h1]Angle of the Gradient[/h1]

As an alternative to predefined directions (bottom, top, right, left, bottom right, etc.), you can control the gradient's direction by specifying an angle.

The angle is specified as an angle extending between a horizontal line and the gradient line. In other words, 0deg creates a left-to right-gradient, while 90deg generates a bottom-to-top gradient.[code format="css" codeId="603"]div.first {
   float: left;
   width: 300px; 
   height: 100px;
   margin: 4px;
   color: #FFF;
   background:-moz-linear-gradient([b]bottom left,[/b] blue, green, white);
}
div.second {
   float: left;
   width: 300px; 
   height: 100px;
   margin: 4px;
   background:-moz-linear-gradient([b]100deg[/b], blue, green, white);
}[/code]
[b]Result:[/b] [img id="2691" width="100%"]
